I had the opportunity to present at SecKC's June 2026 meeting. This was my first professional speaking engagement, and I hope to have more opportunities in the future!

The presentations were recorded on an iPhone 17 Pro and can be found in this [Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1SEKekHE6KlbpKwQFrmc_8b1z2wQ_EapA?usp=sharing)

## Event Information
This was a _chaotic_ SecKC meeting! There were 6 speakers at once, stationed around Knuckleheads Garage. Each presenter gave their talk twice. Meanwhile, there were tattoo artists giving live tattoos on the main stage as a fundraiser for [Hope House](https://www.hopehouse.net/), a local non-profit focused on breaking the cycle of domestic violence. SecKC fundraised **$6,000!** More details can be found on the [event page](https://www.seckc.org/upcoming-events/seckc-june-2026).

## Talk Description

### Title of your talk
Computer Science Education Starts with Community

### Description of the Talk
Access to computer science education in high schools has expanded significantly, but access alone does not guarantee meaningful learning experiences or clear pathways into technology careers. After transitioning from my own technology career into teaching, I saw firsthand how disconnected students can be from real technical career pathways and how little support many educators have in building those opportunities. This session explores the current state of high school CS education, the gap between classroom learning and industry expectations, what I’ve learned rebuilding a CS department, and practical ways local professionals can help support teachers, inspire students, and strengthen the next generation of technology talent.

